0. Executive Summary
============================================================

We tested an alpha=0 lens for RH-like nontrivial zeros.

Define:
  ρ = β + iγ
  α = Re(ρ) - 1/2 = β - 1/2

Then:
  α = 0       critical line / candidate closure ridge
  α ≠ 0       off-ridge candidate / debt generator

The useful numerical locator is not simply:

  N_sm(T) = n

but the half-jump / theta-midpoint correction:

  θ(T)/π = n - 3/2

where θ is the Riemann-Siegel theta function.

Observed pattern:
  N_sm(T)=n has step-right-end bias.
  θ midpoint removes most of this bias.
  Remaining error appears as local phase/S(T)-type debt.
  Hardy Z(t) root refinement can then locate the zero precisely.

Engineering reading:
  α=0 locks the horizontal coordinate.
  θ midpoint aligns the vertical phase.
  Hardy Z(t) refines the root.
  ξ symmetry checks whether the basin is centered at α=0.
  Turing/window count is required to exclude missing off-ridge zeros in a finite window.

The method is a zero locator and certificate pipeline,
not a proof of RH.


