7. Prime-Side Shadow: Li(x), π(x), ψ(x)
============================================================

Distinguish:

  π:
    circle constant in zero density / phase formulas

  π(x):
    prime-counting function

  Li(x):
    logarithmic integral, smooth baseline for π(x)

Prime-side lens:

  π(x) - Li(x)

or cleaner:

  ψ(x) - x

where:

  ψ(x) = Σ_{n≤x} Λ(n)

Riemann explicit-formula reading:

  ψ(x)-x ≈ -Σ_ρ x^ρ / ρ

Let:

  x = e^u

If RH zero:

  ρ = 1/2 + iγ

then:

  x^ρ = e^{u/2} e^{iγu}

Normalize:

  Eψ(u) = e^{-u/2}(ψ(e^u)-e^u)

Then:

  Eψ(u) contains waves with log-frequency γ.

Therefore:

  zero-side:
    θ midpoint predicts γ_n

  prime-side:
    ψ(x)-x or π(x)-Li(x) contains γ_n as a frequency shadow

Use prime-side lens as:
  cross-lens verification,
not as primary locator.

Matched-filter sketch:

  M(γ) = |∫ Eψ(u) exp(-iγu) w(u) du|

Accept candidate frequency if:
  γ near θ-midpoint
  Z(t) root exists near γ
  ξ basin is centered
  prime-side frequency shadow is compatible


